 -- tFormal Protest: Reconsidering the Poetics of Canadian Pamphleteering -- tRadio Poetics: Publishing and Poetry on CBC’s Anthology -- tThe Public Reading: Call for a New Paradigm -- tWe Are the Amp: A Poetics of the Human Microphone -- tCanadian Public Poetics: Negotiating Belonging in a Globalizing World -- tNota bene; or, notes toward a poetics of work . . . -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tBooks in the TransCanada Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPublic Poetics is a collection of essays and poems that address some of the most pressing issues of the discipline in the twenty-first century. The collection brings together fifteen original essays addressing “publics,” “poetry,” and “poetics” from the situated space of Canada while simultaneously troubling the notion of the nation as a stable term. It asks hard questions about who and what count as “publics” in Canada. Critical essays stand alongside poetry as visual and editorial reminders of the cross-pollination required in thinking through both poetry and poetics. Public Poetics is divided into three thematic sections. The first contains essays surveying poetics in the present moment through the lens of the public/private divide, systematic racism in Canada, the counterpublic, feminist poetics, and Canadian innovations on postmodern poetics. The second section contains author-specific studies of public poets. The final section contains essays that use innovative renderings of “poetics” as a means of articulating alternative communities and practices. Each section is paired with a collection of original poetry by ten contemporary Canadian poets. This collection attends to the changing landscape of critical discourse around poetry and poetics in Canada, and will be of use to teachers and students of poetry and poetics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; ti